Tuesday Thoughts
----------------

* Paramount-Skydance
and the =E2=80=98Top Gun=E2=80=99 objection: Mark Zuckerberg may have fired=
 the fact-checkers and canceled the diversity initiatives, but David Elliso=
n=E2=80=99s team at Paramount is taking a decidedly different approach to D=
onald Trump=E2=80=99s second term. They=E2=80=99re betting that the incomin=
g Republican administration will resemble the good old days, when conservat=
ives rolled their eyes at bureaucratic roadblocks to M&A.

But=E2=80=A6 will it? The F.C.C. is still reviewing
Skydance=E2=80=99s takeover of CBS stations as part of the Paramount deal, =
and the outcome is getting more intriguing=E2=80=94largely because incoming=
 F.C.C. chair Brendan Carr wants to address perceived political bias at the=
 network. After Carr expressed this view, an obscure legal group, the Cente=
r for American Rights=E2=80=94the same outfit that, last fall, filed an F.C=
=2EC. complaint to demand the full t=
ranscript of Kamala Harris=E2=80=99s 60 M=
inutes interview=E2=80=94once again entered the
fray. Funded by dark money, the center filed a formal comment in December c=
alling for conditions on the approval of the merger, citing alleged bias at=
