Once upon a time, Hollywood waged a pitched battle against the
VCR. Motion Picture Association chief Jack Valenti infamously told Congress=
 that the home video recording device posed the same threat to the movie an=
d television industries =E2=80=9Cas the Boston strangler [did] to the woman=
 home alone.=E2=80=9D Yet, the industry thrived after the Supreme Court gre=
enlit the disruptive technology in the Sony Betamax case. Now OpenAI, along=
 with Microsoft, is reaching back to the VCR hostilities to defend generati=
ve A.I. On Tuesday, their lawyers urged dismissal
of key claims in The New York Times Company=E2=80=99s high-profile lawsuit =
against Sam Altman=E2=80=99s nonprofit=E2=80=93turned=E2=80=93for-profit ou=
tfit.

=C2=A0

The Times v. OpenAI brawl is just one of more than 35 major cases about to =
set the legal table for generative A.I. But while other cases include osten=
sible bombshells, such as the
revelation ( https://techcrunch.com/2025/01/09/mark-zuckerberg-gave-metas-l=
lama-team-the-ok-to-train-on-copyrighted-works-filing-claims/?utm_campaign=
=3DWhat+I%27m+Hearing%2B+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%281%2F14%2F25%29&utm_content=3DWhat=
+I%27m+Hearing%2B+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%281%2F14%2F25%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action=
&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ) that Mark Zuckerb=
erg personally approved pirated data sets, this particular lawsuit has my a=
ttention, especially since the Times is represented by Susman Godfrey. The =
firm is skilled at netting colossal paydays, including the $787 million tha=
t Fox News paid Dominion Voting
Systems, and the $4.7 billion NFL Sunday Ticket verdict, later overturned a=
nd currently on appeal. Those betting on a quick resolution might want to r=
econsider.

=C2=A0

Today, New York federal district court judge Sidney Stein heard arguments t=
hat had more people listening on a conference line than any hearing I can r=
emember. The session opened with a painstaking tutorial for a perplexed
Stein, delving into =E2=80=9Cretrieval augmentation generation,=E2=80=9D am=
ong other technicalities, with defendants not denying that ChatGPT=E2=80=99=
s training involved some form of copying. Yet, they argued that the Times k=
new of the reproductions many years ago, outside the statute of limitations=
, citing the publication=E2=80=99s own reporting. The Times=E2=80=99s rebut=
tal was that it hardly had adequate notice, given OpenAI=E2=80=99s nonprofi=
t facade.

=C2=A0

The defense pivoted to emphasize the transformative purpose of generative A=
=2EI.=E2=80=94say, to take articles about=20=
the court system, to use an example=
 offered by OpenAI lawyer Andrew Gass, and create a poem about 500 Pearl St=
reet, the location of today=E2=80=99s hearing. That circles us back ( https=
://www.oyez.org/cases/1982/81-1687?utm_campaign=3DWhat+I%27m+Hearing%2B+-+S=
UBSCRIBERS+%281%2F14%2F25%29&utm_content=3DWhat+I%27m+Hearing%2B+-+SUBSCRIB=
ERS+%281%2F14%2F25%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&ut=
m_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ) to the Betamax opinion, which stands for the =
precedent that
manufacturers of technologies capable of non-infringing uses are not liable=
 for contributory copyright infringement. The defendants are shooting for t=
hat same principle to be applied here. =E2=80=9CThe doctrine absolves =E2=
=80=A6 mere understanding that the product will be misused,=E2=80=9D argued=
 Gass.

=C2=A0

Susman Godfrey partner Ian Crosby countered that, back in the =E2=80=9980s,=
 Sony didn=E2=80=99t preload its VCRs with
millions of movies and TV shows, nor did Sony oversee how buyers were opera=
ting it. =E2=80=9CWhereas here, they are selling a service built on copyrig=
hted works and continuing to operate it,=E2=80=9D he said, arguing that bec=
ause of the company=E2=80=99s continued oversight, one can infer its knowle=
dge that some users might be doing things like using ChatGPT to evade paywa=
lls. In written briefing, the Times lawyers also added, =E2=80=9CIf VCRs ha=
d been built with movies to make movies that compete with movies, =E2=80=A6=
 [the]
Sony [Supreme Court ruling] would have gone the other way.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0

=C2=A0

Anyone expecting a quick decision from the judge came away disappointed. St=
ill, there were subtle signs that Stein wasn=E2=80=99t prepared to let the =
defendants off the hook. Much of what was discussed seemed to turn on factu=
al issues, which the judge noted at several points. And that=E2=80=99s not =
something that will be resolved at the
motion-to-dismiss phase. As for the all-important topic of fair use, that=
=E2=80=99s a debate everyone expects will have to be resolved at trial.=C2=
=A0

=C2=A0

I=E2=80=99m sure once this proceeding gets there, OpenAI and Microsoft will=
 have further opportunities to tell a jury the old lesson about the industr=
y=E2=80=99s VCR problem, with the Times and its Susman Godfrey team respond=
ing with tales of greedy tech companies encroaching on entire
industries. Whether this narrative will echo the catastrophic predictions o=
f yesteryear remains to be seen, but its impact could be as profound as the=
 landmark cases of the past.=C2=A0

TikTok=E2=80=99s Supreme Test
-----------------------

Any day now, we=E2=80=99ll learn the fate of the law requiring TikTok=E2=80=
=99s
Chinese parent, ByteDance, to divest from the social media platform or face=
 a U.S. ban. After tuning into the Supreme Court hearing last Friday, I=E2=
=80=99d wager the law is likely to survive. But don=E2=80=99t expect a bold=
, sweeping opinion. This could easily become one of those fractured rulings=
 with concurring opinions galore, leaving little in the way of a clear prec=
edent. And if the justices do coalesce around a single rationale=E2=80=94sa=
y, Chief Justice John Roberts=E2=80=99 skepticism over whether
regulating TikTok=E2=80=99s corporate structure even counts as restricting =
speech=E2=80=94the opinion seems likely to be written as narrowly as possib=
le.

=C2=A0

On the free speech issue, TikTok could lose for a variety of reasons, not l=
east because the justices seemed to struggle with the nature of the =E2=80=
=9Cexpression=E2=80=9D at stake. A U.S. subsidiary of a Chinese company, cl=
early under Beijing state influence, leveraging an A.I.-driven
algorithm? That doesn=E2=80=99t exactly evoke the image of someone standing=
 on a soapbox in the town square. Noel Francisco, TikTok=E2=80=99s lawyer, =
has argued the algorithm reflects the company=E2=80=99s editorial judgment =
about the best mix of videos, but the justices may conclude the speech here=
 is too abstract=E2=80=94and that=E2=80=99s before you get to the U.S. gove=
rnment=E2=80=99s claimed national-security interest.

=C2=A0

The
justices did appear sympathetic to arguments from TikTok creators, represen=
ted by separate counsel. But how far does that sympathy go? Justice Alito l=
ikened TikTok to an old, comfy shirt: It feels good, but you can always fin=
d a replacement. Justice Jackson took things a step further, reframing the =
issue as a matter of association=E2=80=94our ability to connect with whomev=
er we choose. Important, yes, but perhaps less so than the C.C.P. manipulat=
ing your kids.
(Check out the transcript ( https://www.supremecourt.gov/oral_arguments/arg=
ument_transcripts/2024/24-656_1an2.pdf?utm_campaign=3DWhat+I%27m+Hearing%2B=
+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%281%2F14%2F25%29&utm_content=3DWhat+I%27m+Hearing%2B+-+SUBS=
CRIBERS+%281%2F14%2F25%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.i=
o&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ) for yourself.)

=C2=A0

What=E2=80=99s the likely outcome? There=E2=80=99s enough murkiness that a =
majority of justices=E2=80=94perhaps excluding Gorsuch and Sotomayor=E2=80=
=94will likely uphold the law. But I don=E2=80=99t think anyone in the free
speech business should find this reassuring. Even a carefully written opini=
on upholding the TikTok ban could provide a loose roadmap for future censor=
s. And while this opinion might not necessarily become a landmark First Ame=
ndment precedent=E2=80=94perhaps we=E2=80=99ll eventually regard it as a Bu=
sh v. Gore-style oddity=E2=80=94it=E2=80=99s poised to leave an unsettling =
mark on the landscape of digital expression.

=C2=A0

On a
practical level, will the ruling send TikTok packing? That=E2=80=99s also c=
omplicated. In one of the weirder moves in SCOTUS history, Donald Trump ess=
entially begged the justices, via amicus brief, for time to work his Art of=
 the Deal voodoo with the Chinese. The law is set to take effect on January=
 19, one day before he is sworn into office. Solicitor General Elizabeth Pr=
elogar pointed out a key problem with granting a temporary injunction: Typi=
cally, granting
a stay suggests the appellant (TikTok) is likely to prevail on the merits. =
Sure, the justices could bend that principle, but are they going to nullify=
 an act of Congress just to make Trump happy? (Well, a few of them might.)

=C2=A0

Let=E2=80=99s say the law goes into effect. Apple and Google would then fac=
e $5,000-per-user penalties for keeping TikTok in their app stores, which w=
ould bring their tab to about $600
billion apiece. Oracle would face similar fines for hosting TikTok=E2=80=99=
s data. Could Trump simply issue an executive order saying he won=E2=80=99t=
 enforce the penalties?=C2=A0

=C2=A0

Justice Kavanaugh floated that possibility during oral arguments and came a=
way thinking that=E2=80=99s unlikely to be the resolution. Sotomayor drove =
the point home by getting Prelogar to confirm that the statute of limitatio=
ns is
five years=E2=80=94meaning a future White House administration could theore=
tically prosecute Apple and Google for the violations. So even if Trump shr=
ugs off enforcement, companies won=E2=80=99t risk hundreds of billions of d=
ollars on a wink from Trump and some hopeful due-process defense.

=C2=A0

There=E2=80=99s another wild card (or two, if you credit the scenario, floa=
ted in news outlets this week, that Trump=E2=80=99s exit from his TikTok di=
lemma will be to
arrange its sale to his pal Elon.) Presuming the law stands, a TikTok dives=
titure happens when the president says it happens. Which means Trump could =
strike a deal with the Chinese that falls short of a true divestiture, but =
is packaged as one. I=E2=80=99ve seen nothing in the law that prevents this=
=2E It=E2=80=99s easy to imagine the scene=
: Trump declares victory, the Chine=
se agree to some vague concessions, TikTok stays alive, and everyone preten=
ds they got what they wanted. Now that
sounds like Trump.

