>Paramount-Skydance
and the =E2=80=98Top Gun=E2=80=99 objection</em>:<strong> Mark Zuckerberg</=
strong> may have fired the fact-checkers and canceled the diversity initiat=
ives, but <strong>David Ellison</strong>=E2=80=99s team at Paramount is tak=
ing a decidedly different approach to <strong>Donald Trump</strong>=E2=80=
=99s second term. They=E2=80=99re betting that the incoming Republican admi=
nistration will resemble the good old days, when conservatives rolled their=
 eyes at bureaucratic roadblocks to M&amp;A.<br/><br/>But=E2=80=A6 will it?=
 The F.C.C. is still reviewing
Skydance=E2=80=99s takeover of CBS stations as part of the Paramount deal, =
and the outcome is getting more intriguing=E2=80=94largely because incoming=
 F.C.C. chair <strong>Brendan Carr</strong> wants to address perceived poli=
tical bias at the network. After Carr expressed this view, an obscure legal=
 group, the Center for American Rights=E2=80=94the same outfit that, last f=
all, filed an F.C.C. complaint to demand the full transcript of <strong>Kam=
ala Harris</strong>=E2=80=99s <em>60 Minutes </em>interview=E2=80=94once ag=
ain entered the
fray. Funded by dark money, the center filed a formal comment in December c=
alling for conditions on the approval of the merger, citing alleged bias at=
 <em>60 Minutes</em>, the broadcaster=E2=80=99s D.E.I. hiring efforts, and =
undue foreign influence. The center claims that China=E2=80=99s Tencent Hol=
dings, an investor in Skydance, exerted itself by getting the Taiwanese fla=
g removed from <strong>Tom Cruise</strong>=E2=80=99s pilot jacket in <em>To=
p Gun: Maverick</em>.=C2=A0<br/><br/>Earlier this month, Skydance fired
back, challenging the center=E2=80=99s standing to object and rejecting man=
y of its claims outright. Skydance emphasized Tencent=E2=80=99s minor, nonv=
oting stake, and argued that concerns about bias are largely about the medi=
a industry in <em>general</em>, and that imposing any viewpoint conditions =
would violate the First Amendment. The center and others who=E2=80=99ve obj=
ected are set to respond later this week, leaving the timing of a final F.C=
=2EC. vote up in the air.<br/><br/>If the F.C.C. votes down the Skydance
transaction, it would set off a First Amendment challenge that=E2=80=99d be=
 a worthy successor to the TikTok ban case. But the more pressing question =
is whether the commissioners designate the transaction for a hearing. That =
would throw the deal into administrative purgatory, potentially killing it,=
 as happened with Tegna and Standard General a few years ago. While the F.C=
