alt:
28.799999999999997px;"><strong>TikTok=E2=80=99s Supreme Test</strong></h3>
</td></tr></tbody></table>
<table class=3D"c4" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellpadding=3D"0" cellspaci=
ng=3D"0" role=3D"presentation" style=3D"mso-table-lspace:0pt;mso-table-rspa=
ce:0pt;word-break:break-word;"><tbody><tr><td class=3D"r" style=3D"padding-=
bottom:32px;"><div style=3D"color:#000000;direction:ltr;font-family:&#39;In=
ter&#39;,&#39;Arial&#39;;font-size:17px;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:0px;=
line-height:150%;text-align:left;mso-line-height-alt:25.5px;"><p style=3D"m=
argin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Any day now, we=E2=80=99ll learn the fate of th=
e law requiring TikTok=E2=80=99s
Chinese parent, ByteDance, to divest from the social media platform or face=
 a U.S. ban. After tuning into the Supreme Court hearing last Friday, I=E2=
=80=99d wager the law is likely to survive. But don=E2=80=99t expect a bold=
, sweeping opinion. This could easily become one of those fractured rulings=
 with concurring opinions galore, leaving little in the way of a clear prec=
edent. And if the justices do coalesce around a single rationale=E2=80=94sa=
y, Chief Justice <strong>John Roberts</strong>=E2=80=99 skepticism over whe=
ther
regulating TikTok=E2=80=99s corporate structure even counts as restricting =
speech=E2=80=94the opinion seems likely to be written as narrowly as possib=
le.</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margi=
n:0;margin-bottom:0px;">On the free speech issue, TikTok could lose for a v=
ariety of reasons, not least because the justices seemed to struggle with t=
he nature of the =E2=80=9Cexpression=E2=80=9D at stake. A U.S. subsidiary o=
f a Chinese company, clearly under Beijing state influence, leveraging an A=
=2EI.-driven
<em>algorithm</em>? That doesn=E2=80=99t exactly evoke the image of someone=
 standing on a soapbox in the town square. <strong>Noel Francisco</strong>,=
 TikTok=E2=80=99s lawyer, has argued the algorithm reflects the company=E2=
=80=99s editorial judgment about the best mix of videos, but the justices m=
ay conclude the speech here is too abstract=E2=80=94and that=E2=80=99s befo=
re you get to the U.S. government=E2=80=99s claimed national-security inter=
est.</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"marg=
in:0;margin-bottom:0px;">The
justices <em>did</em> appear sympathetic to arguments from TikTok creators,=
 represented by separate counsel. But how far does that sympathy go? Justic=
e <strong>Alito</strong> likened TikTok to an old, comfy shirt: It feels go=
od, but you can always find a replacement. Justice <strong>Jackson</strong>=
 took things a step further, reframing the issue as a matter of association=
=E2=80=94our ability to connect with whomever we choose. Important, yes, bu=
t perhaps less so than the C.C.P. manipulating your kids.
(Check out the <a href=3D"https://email.puck.news/e/c/eyJlbWFpbF9pZCI6ImRnV=
DJ4Z1lEQUt2UktxclJLZ0dVWjN3bncxbkJibjVGV1BMMXQ4OD0iLCJocmVmIjoiaHR0cHM6Ly93=
d3cuc3VwcmVtZWNvdXJ0Lmdvdi9vcmFsX2FyZ3VtZW50cy9hcmd1bWVudF90cmFuc2NyaXB0cy8=
yMDI0LzI0LTY1Nl8xYW4yLnBkZj91dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249V2hhdCtJJTI3bStIZWFyaW5nJTJCKy=
0rU1VCU0NSSUJFUlMrJTI4MSUyRjE0JTJGMjUlMjlcdTAwMjZ1dG1fY29udGVudD1XaGF0K0klM=
jdtK0hlYXJpbmclMkIrLStTVUJTQ1JJQkVSUyslMjgxJTJGMTQlMkYyNSUyOVx1MDAyNnV0bV9t=
ZWRpdW09ZW1haWxfYWN0aW9uXHUwMDI2dXRtX3NvdXJjZT1jdXN0b21lci5pb1x1MDAyNnV0bV9=
0ZXJtPWY2YzYwNjE3ZGE0MmFiZDEyYSIsImludGVybmFsIjoiZjZjNjA2MTdkYTQyYWJkMTJhIi=
wibGlua19pZCI6MjA0NDY3Mn0/e4350038b5f031408e1917094484d578feaf49d2bf0c65c50=
b6e882543a42e05" style=3D"text-decoration:underline;color:#d40000;">transcr=
ipt</a> for yourself.)</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</=
p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">What=E2=80=99s the likely outcom=
e? There=E2=80=99s enough murkiness that a majority of justices=E2=80=94per=
haps excluding <strong>Gorsuch</strong> and <strong>Sotomayor</strong>=E2=
=80=94will likely uphold the law. But I don=E2=80=99t think anyone in the f=
ree
speech business should find this reassuring. Even a carefully written opini=
on upholding the TikTok ban could provide a loose roadmap for future censor=
s. And while this opinion might not necessarily become a landmark First Ame=
ndment precedent=E2=80=94perhaps we=E2=80=99ll eventually regard it as a <e=
m>Bush v. Gore</em>-style oddity=E2=80=94it=E2=80=99s poised to leave an un=
settling mark on the landscape of digital expression.</p><p style=3D"margin=
:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">O=
n a
practical level, will the ruling send TikTok packing? That=E2=80=99s also c=
omplicated. In one of the weirder moves in SCOTUS history, <strong>Donald T=
rump</strong> essentially begged the justices, via amicus brief, for time t=
o work his <em>Art of the Deal</em> voodoo with the Chinese. The law is set=
 to take effect on January 19, one day before he is sworn into office. Soli=
citor General <strong>Elizabeth Prelogar</strong> pointed out a key problem=
 with granting a temporary injunction: Typically, granting
a stay suggests the appellant (TikTok) is likely to prevail on the merits. =
Sure, the justices could bend that principle, but are they going to nullify=
 an act of Congress just to make Trump happy? (Well, a few of them might.)<=
/p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;=
margin-bottom:0px;">Let=E2=80=99s say the law goes into effect. Apple and G=
oogle would then face $5,000-per-user penalties for keeping TikTok in their=
 app stores, which would bring their tab to about <em>$600
billion </em>apiece. Oracle would face similar fines for hosting TikTok=E2=
=80=99s data. Could Trump simply issue an executive order saying he won=E2=
=80=99t enforce the penalties?=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:=
0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Justice <strong>Ka=
vanaugh</strong> floated that possibility during oral arguments and came aw=
ay thinking that=E2=80=99s unlikely to be the resolution. Sotomayor drove t=
he point home by getting Prelogar to confirm that the statute of limitation=
s is
five years=E2=80=94meaning a future White House administration could theore=
tically prosecute Apple and Google for the violations. So even if Trump shr=
ugs off enforcement, companies won=E2=80=99t risk hundreds of billions of d=
ollars on a wink from Trump and some hopeful due-process defense.</p><p sty=
le=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;">There=
=E2=80=99s another wild card (or two, if you credit the scenario, floated i=
n news outlets this week, that Trump=E2=80=99s exit from his TikTok dilemma=
 will be to
arrange its sale to his pal <strong>Elon</strong>.) Presuming the law stand=
s, a TikTok divestiture happens when the president says it happens. Which m=
eans Trump could strike a deal with the Chinese that falls short of a true =
divestiture, but is packaged as one. I=E2=80=99ve seen nothing in the law t=
hat prevents this. It=E2=80=99s easy to imagine the scene: Trump declares v=
ictory, the Chinese agree to some vague concessions, TikTok stays alive, an=
d everyone pretends they got what they wanted. Now <em>that</em>
sounds like Trump.</p></div>
</td></tr></tbody></table>
